label("$\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$", A, N);
label("$\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$", B, S);
label("$k \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$", C, E);
[/asy]

The vector $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} - k \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ is orthogonal to $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix},$ so
\[\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} - k \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 2k \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}\]is orthogonal to $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.$  This means their dot product is 0:
\[\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2k \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 2k \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} = 0.\]This reduces to $8k = 20,$ so $k = \frac{5}{2}.$  Therefore, the projection of $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$ onto $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ is $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}.$

Solution:
The projection of $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$ onto $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ is the vector that is a scalar multiple of $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ and lies on the line spanned by $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.$  Thus, the projection is of the form $\begin{pmatrix} c \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.$

[asy]
usepackage("amsmath");

unitsize(0.6 cm);

pair A, B, P, Q;

A = (4,5);
B = (2,0);
P = (A + reflect(B,(0,0))*(A))/2;
Q = (A - reflect(B,(0,0))*(A))/2;

draw((-1,0)--(6,0));
draw((0,-1)--(0,8));
draw((0,0)--A,Arrow(6));
draw((0,0)--B,Arrow(6));
draw((0,0)--P,dashed,Arrow(6));
draw(A--P,dashed,Arrow(6));
draw(A--Q,dashed,Arrow(6));

label("$\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$", A, N);
label("$\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$", B, S);
label("$\begin{pmatrix} c \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$", P, S);
label("$\begin{pmatrix} 4 - c \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$", Q, N);
[/asy]

Since the projection of $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$ onto $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ lies on the line spanned by $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix},$ the vector $\begin{pmatrix} 4 - c \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$ is orthogonal to $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.$  Hence,
\[\begin{pmatrix} 4 - c \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} = 0.\]This gives us $(4 - c) \cdot 2 = 0,$ so $c = \boxed{2}.$

